"Dedysh S.N., Panikov N.S., Liesack W., Großkopf R., Zhou J., Tiedje J.M.","Isolation of acidophilic methane-oxidizing bacteria from Northern Peat Wetlands",1998,"Science","282","5387",,"281","284",,,10.1126/science.282.5387.281,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0032500735&partnerID=40&md5=c51393a8c2db163155557af1ba5f8dd9","Institute of Microbiology, Russian Academy of Sciences, Moscow 117811, Russian Federation; Center for Microbial Ecology, Michigan State University, East Lansing, MI 48824-1325, United States; Max-Planck-Inst. F. Terrestrische M., D-35043 Marburg, Germany","Dedysh, S.N., Institute of Microbiology, Russian Academy of Sciences, Moscow 117811, Russian Federation, Center for Microbial Ecology, Michigan State University, East Lansing, MI 48824-1325, United States; Panikov, N.S., Institute of Microbiology, Russian Academy of Sciences, Moscow 117811, Russian Federation; Liesack, W., Max-Planck-Inst. F. Terrestrische M., D-35043 Marburg, Germany; Großkopf, R., Max-Planck-Inst. F. Terrestrische M., D-35043 Marburg, Germany; Zhou, J., Center for Microbial Ecology, Michigan State University, East Lansing, MI 48824-1325, United States; Tiedje, J.M., Center for Microbial Ecology, Michigan State University, East Lansing, MI 48824-1325, United States","Acidic northern wetlands are an important source of methane, one of the gases that contributes to global warming. Methane oxidation in the surface of these acidic wetlands can reduce the methane flux to the atmosphere up to 90 percent. Here the isolation of three methanotropic microorganisms from three boreal forest sites is reported. They are moderately acidophilic organisms and have a soluble methane monooxygenase. In contrast to the known groups of methanotrophs, 16S ribosomal DNA sequence analysis shows that they are affiliated with the acidophilic heterotropic bacterium Beijerinckia indica subsp. indica.",,"biogeochemical cycle; methane; peat; soil microorganism; wetland; amino acid sequence; article; bacterial gene; bacterial genetics; bacterium isolation; gene sequence; methylococcaceae; nonhuman; priority journal; Amino Acid Sequence; DNA, Bacterial; DNA, Ribosomal; Evolution; Genes, Bacterial; Gram-Negative Aerobic Rods and Cocci; Hydrogen-Ion Concentration; Methane; Methylococcaceae; Molecular Sequence Data; Oxidation-Reduction; Oxygenases; Phylogeny; RNA, Ribosomal, 16S; Russia; Sequence Alignment; Siberia; Soil Microbiology; Solubility; Bacteria (microorganisms); Beijerinckia; Beijerinckia indica subsp. indica; Methylococcaceae","GENBANK: AF004554, Y17144","DNA, Bacterial; DNA, Ribosomal; Methane, 74-82-8; Oxygenases, 1.13.-; RNA, Ribosomal, 16S; methane monooxygenase, 1.14.13.25",,,,"Khalil, M.A.K., Rasmussen, R.A., (1985) Atmos. Environ., 19, p. 397; (1997) World Meteorological Organization WDCGC Data Report, 4 (12), pp. 47-115. , Japan Meteorological Agency; Matthews, E., Fung, I., (1987) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 1, p. 61; Hein, R., Crutzen, P.J., Heimann, M., (1997) Global Biogeochem. Cycles, 11, p. 43; Fung, I., (1991) J. Geophys. Res., 96, p. 13033; Hanson, R.S., Netrusov, A.I., Truji, K., (1991) The Procaryotes, pp. 661-684. , A. Balows et al., Eds. Springer-Verlag, New York; King, G.M., (1992) Adv. Microb. Ecol., 12, p. 431; Yavitt, J.B., (1990) Soil Biol. Biochem., 22, p. 441; Panikov, N.S., (1993) J. Ecol. Chem., 1, p. 7; Krumholz, L.R., (1995) FEMS Microbiol. Ecol., 18, p. 215; Sundh, I., (1995) FEMS Microbiol. Ecol., 18, p. 103; McDonald, I.R., Kenna, E.M., Murrell, J.C., (1995) Appl. Environ. Microbiol., 61, p. 116; McDonald, I.R., (1996) FEMS Microbiol. Ecol., 21, p. 197; Hanson, R.S., Hanson, T.E., (1996) Microbiol. Rev., 60, p. 439; Dedysh, S.N., Panikov, N.S., Tiedje, J.M., (1998) Appl. Environ. Microbiol., 64, p. 922; notenotenotenoteDedysh, S.N., Panikov, N.S., (1997) Mikrobiologiya, 66, p. 563; Mikrobiologiya, p. 569; Dunfield, P., Knowles, R., Moore, T.R., (1993) Soil Biol. Biochem., 25, p. 321; Amaral, J.A., Ren, T., Know